</style>
</head>
<body>
<canvas id=“waveform”></canvas>

<script>
var canvas = document.getElementById(‘waveform’);
var ctx = canvas.getContext(‘2d’);
var waveformHeight = 16;
var animationDuration = 2000; // Total duration (in milliseconds)
var start = null;

function animate(timestamp) {
  if (!start) start = timestamp;
  var progress = timestamp - start;
  var offset = ((progress % animationDuration) / animationDuration) * (canvas.width + waveformHeight);

  ctx.clearRect(0, 0, canvas.width, canvas.height);
  ctx.fillStyle = ‘blue’;

  for (var x = -waveformHeight; x < canvas.width; x += waveformHeight * 2) {
    var y = Math.sin((x + offset) / (canvas.width + waveformHeight) * Math.PI * 2) * waveformHeight;
    ctx.fillRect(x, (canvas.height - y) / 2, waveformHeight, y);
  }

  requestAnimationFrame(animate);
}

animate();

window.addEventListener(‘resize’, function() {
  canvas.width = window.innerWidth;
});

</script>
</body>
</html>



In this example, the JavaScript code uses the canvas element to draw a waveform animation. The waveform is created using a sine wave function and is continuously updated based on the animation duration. By adjusting the waveformHeight and animationDuration variables, you can customize the waveform animation to your liking.

